      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Rollout date</span><span class="meta-value">December 2021</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>The <strong>Google Vicinity Update</strong> was a significant local search algorithm change that rolled out in December 2021, increasing the weight of physical proximity as a ranking factor in Google's local pack. Businesses that previously dominated an entire metro area from one location saw their visible radius shrink dramatically — while nearby smaller competitors gained visibility they couldn't achieve before.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Rollout date</div>
            <div class="tms-value">December 2021</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary signal shifted</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Proximity (distance)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Last comparable</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Possum Update (2016)</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Before Vicinity, a dental practice with 500 reviews could rank in the local pack for searches 15 miles away. After Vicinity, that same practice only appears for searches within a tighter geographic radius — proximity now outweighs prominence for most queries. Understanding this update is the foundation of any local SEO strategy built after 2022.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is the Google Vicinity Update?</h2>
        <p>The Google Vicinity Update is an algorithm change to Google's local search ranking system that permanently increased how much physical distance between searcher and business affects local pack positioning. It rolled out in December 2021 and caused the most widespread ranking changes in local search since the Google Possum Update in September 2016.</p>
        <p>Google's local algorithm has always weighed three signals to determine local pack rankings:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relevance</strong> — how well the business matches the search query</li>
          <li><strong>Distance</strong> — how close the business is to the searcher</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence</strong> — how well-known the business is (reviews, citations, backlinks, GBP completeness)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Vicinity shifted the balance of these signals so distance carries significantly more weight. Before December 2021, a business with overwhelming prominence could rank across an entire metro area. After Vicinity, proximity became the dominant filter — prominence still matters, but it can no longer compensate for being far from the searcher.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Two secondary effects of the Vicinity Update</div>
          <p>Beyond the distance reweighting, Vicinity also <strong>reduced the ranking power of keyword-stuffed business names</strong> on Google Business Profile. Businesses that added keywords like "Best Dentist Dallas | Emergency Dental | Implants" to their GBP name gained less benefit from that tactic after the update. It also <strong>diminished centroid bias</strong> — the old tendency for businesses near the geographic centre of a city to rank better across the whole area.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why the Google Vicinity Update matters for local SEO</h2>
        <p>The Vicinity Update permanently changed the economics of local pack visibility. Four reasons it belongs in every local SEO practitioner's mental model:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Proximity now outweighs prominence.</strong> Being close to the searcher matters more than having the most reviews. A business with 50 reviews a half-mile away regularly outranks a competitor with 500 reviews 5 miles away for most queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Smaller businesses gained visibility.</strong> Single-location businesses that were previously overshadowed by dominant multi-location chains or review-rich competitors finally appear in local results for searches near their physical location.</li>
          <li><strong>GBP name spam became less effective.</strong> Keyword stuffing in business names is a policy violation AND less effective post-Vicinity. That's a useful double disincentive for reporting competitors who still do it.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-location strategy changed.</strong> Businesses with multiple locations now see each location's visibility become more geographically contained — which makes each location's GBP optimisation more important independently.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How the Google Vicinity Update works</h2>

        <h3>Increased distance weighting</h3>
        <p>Google's ranking algorithm assigns numerical weights to each local signal. Vicinity shifted those weights so that distance — the physical kilometres between searcher and business — now produces a larger score penalty for businesses outside the immediate area. A business 1 mile away consistently outranks a more prominent competitor 5 miles away unless that competitor's prominence advantage is enormous.</p>

        <h3>Reduced keyword-name impact</h3>
        <p>Before Vicinity, a business named "Best Plumber Austin | Emergency Plumbing | 24/7 Repairs" gained meaningful ranking advantages from those keywords in its name. Vicinity reduced this signal's contribution to ranking. Google's guidelines prohibit keyword stuffing in business names — Vicinity made enforcement more effective by reducing the reward.</p>

        <h3>What still drives ranking post-Vicinity</h3>
        <p>Proximity is now the dominant filter, but within a given proximity radius, prominence signals still determine who ranks first. That means:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Review count and recency matter within your proximity zone</li>
          <li>GBP completeness (hours, photos, services, posts) influences ranking</li>
          <li>Citation consistency across directories remains a baseline signal</li>
          <li>Hyperlocal content targeting your immediate service area strengthens your position</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Before Vicinity vs. after Vicinity</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Before Vicinity (pre-Dec 2021)</th><th>After Vicinity (Dec 2021+)</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Primary ranking driver</strong></td><td>Prominence (reviews, citations, links)</td><td class="cell-yes">Proximity (distance to searcher)</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Geographic reach</strong></td><td>Entire metro area (15-25 miles possible)</td><td class="cell-meh">Tighter radius (~5-8 miles typical)</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Who benefits most</strong></td><td>High-review, dominant businesses</td><td>Nearby smaller competitors</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Name spam effectiveness</strong></td><td>High — keyword names boosted rankings</td><td class="cell-no">Reduced — and still a policy violation</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Centroid bias</strong></td><td>Strong — city centre businesses ranked wider</td><td class="cell-meh">Diminished significantly</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Google Vicinity Update examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1: The plumber who lost the metro</h3>
        <p>Before Vicinity: a plumber with 400 reviews in north Dallas ranked first in the local pack for "plumber near me" searches across the entire DFW metro — including searches from customers 25 miles away in the southern suburbs. After Vicinity, that same plumber now only appears for searches within roughly 8 miles of their location. Plumbers in south Dallas and Fort Worth finally appear for their own local searches.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: The restaurant that was invisible</h3>
        <p>A single-location restaurant with 80 reviews was invisible in local results — overshadowed by a chain with 2,000 reviews two miles away. The Vicinity Update gave their proximity advantage enough weight to overcome that review count gap. They now appear consistently in the local pack for searches within 2 miles of their address.</p>

        <h3>Example 3: The dental group adapting strategy</h3>
        <p>A 4-location dental group previously managed all local SEO from their flagship location's GBP. After Vicinity, each location's individual GBP needed its own review strategy, its own localised content, and its own citation profile. Their aggregate search visibility actually increased — because now each location dominated its own zone rather than competing against each other.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local SEO vs. national SEO — how Vicinity changes the playbook</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local SEO (post-Vicinity)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Hyper-local content targeting nearby neighbourhoods</li>
              <li>Reviews from customers physically close to you</li>
              <li>GBP address must be accurate — no P.O. boxes</li>
              <li>Citations from nearby local organisations</li>
              <li>Each location needs independent optimisation</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>National SEO (not affected by Vicinity)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Organic rankings unaffected by Vicinity</li>
              <li>Local pack visibility still limited by radius</li>
              <li>Broad keyword content still drives organic traffic</li>
              <li>E-commerce and national service sites unchanged</li>
              <li>No proximity penalty in standard organic results</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for ranking after the Vicinity Update</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Optimise each location independently.</strong> Each physical location needs its own GBP, its own review strategy, its own local citation profile. Don't manage them as a single entity.</li>
          <li><strong>Generate reviews from nearby customers.</strong> Reviews from customers in your immediate geographic radius carry more signal weight post-Vicinity than reviews from far-away customers. Ask for reviews at the point of service.</li>
          <li><strong>Build hyperlocal content.</strong> Publish neighbourhood-specific pages — "[service] in [neighbourhood]" — that signal your relevance to the micro-areas around your location.</li>
          <li><strong>Report GBP name spam.</strong> Competitors stuffing keywords into their GBP name is a policy violation. Report it. Post-Vicinity, the ranking benefit to them is smaller anyway — but eliminating it is still worth doing.</li>
          <li><strong>Use service area settings carefully.</strong> If you're a service area business, setting a realistic service area in your GBP helps Google understand your actual reach. Inflating the service area doesn't extend your local pack visibility post-Vicinity.</li>
          <li><strong>Open additional locations strategically.</strong> The only reliable way to extend local pack coverage across a metro area is physical presence in each area. Multi-location strategy is now the primary tool for wide geographic coverage.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — trying to rank citywide from one location</div>
          <p>Post-Vicinity, a single location cannot dominate an entire metro area through prominence signals alone. Businesses that continue investing in review volume to extend geographic reach are solving the wrong problem. The fix for geographic coverage is physical presence, not more reviews.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes after the Vicinity Update</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Blaming the update for normal ranking volatility.</strong> Vicinity was a major shift in December 2021. Current ranking changes are likely other factors — not residual Vicinity effects.</li>
          <li><strong>Continuing to stuff keywords in the GBP name.</strong> Less effective post-Vicinity and still a policy violation that can get your GBP suspended.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring neighbourhood-level content.</strong> "Service in [city]" pages are less impactful than "service in [neighbourhood]" pages post-Vicinity.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating all locations' GBPs identically.</strong> Each location needs a strategy tuned to its own proximity zone and local competitive landscape.</li>
          <li><strong>Expecting organic rank to fix local pack visibility.</strong> Organic SEO and local pack are separate systems. Strong organic rankings don't directly improve local pack positions.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is the Vicinity Update still active?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. The Vicinity Update is permanently integrated into Google's local ranking algorithm. The increased weight of proximity is the new normal — it wasn't a temporary test or a bug that was reverted.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I still rank outside my immediate area?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>With strong enough prominence signals, yes — but the radius is much smaller than before Vicinity. Multiple physical locations, service area business settings, and hyper-local content for specific neighbourhoods can extend your reach. Expecting to rank 20 miles away from a single location is unrealistic for most businesses now.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Did the Vicinity Update hurt all businesses equally?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. It hurt businesses that relied on dominating large geographic areas from a single location — especially high-review competitors that previously outranked nearby smaller businesses. It helped nearby smaller businesses that were previously invisible. Net effect: more localised and more fair results.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How can I improve local rankings after the Vicinity Update?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Focus on hyper-local signals: generate reviews from customers in your immediate service area, build citations from nearby organisations, create localised content targeting neighbourhoods around your location, and ensure your GBP address is accurate and your service area is realistic.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does Vicinity affect organic search rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. The Vicinity Update affected only the local pack (the map results and 3-pack). Organic blue-link rankings use different signals and were not directly changed by this update. Local pack and organic results are separate ranking systems.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

